Depth-First Search (DFS) for Graphs ğŸŒ²
ğŸ§  Logic: Depth-First Search (DFS) is a graph traversal algorithm that explores as far as possible along each branch before backtracking. It goes $\mathbf{deep}$ down one path until it hits a dead end (a node with no unvisited neighbors).DFS typically uses a Stack data structure or, more commonly in recursive programming, the function call stack (Recursion). It is often used for topological sorting, finding connected components, and cycle detection.ğŸ“Œ Example:Graph: A -> B, A -> C, B -> D, C -> E

Start at A.
1. Visit A. Go to B.
2. Visit B. Go to D.
3. Visit D. (Dead end). Backtrack to B.
4. Backtrack to A. Go to C.
5. Visit C. Go to E.
...
Order of visit: A, B, D, C, E (Example path)
ğŸ¤¹â€â™€ï¸ Java Code (Conceptual Recursive DFS):Javapublic class DFS {
    public static void dfsTraversal(int u, ArrayList<ArrayList<Integer>> adj, boolean[] visited) {
        visited[u] = true;
        System.out.print(u + " ");

        // Recurse for all neighbors
        for (int v : adj.get(u)) {
            if (!visited[v]) {
                dfsTraversal(v, adj, visited);
            }
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Assume graph 'g' is initialized with V vertices and edges
        // boolean[] visited = new boolean[g.V];
        // dfsTraversal(0, g.adj, visited); // Start from node 0
    }
}
